hands_on_practices.solution:
The appropriate starting point is the definition of velocity as displacement per unit time. If the sample drifts relative to the tip with a constant velocity vector $\mathbf{v}_{\text{d}}$, then the true position of a point on the sample in the sample frame, $\mathbf{r}_{\text{true}}(t)$, and the nominal scanner position, $\mathbf{r}_{\text{scan}}(t)$, are related by
$$
\mathbf{r}_{\text{true}}(t) \;=\; \mathbf{r}_{\text{scan}}(t) \;+\; \mathbf{v}_{\text{d}}\, t,
$$
because at each time increment $dt$, the sample advances by $\mathbf{v}_{\text{d}}\, dt$ relative to the scanner.

In a raster scan, the fast-scan coordinate $x$ advances rapidly during a line, while the slow-scan coordinate $y$ increments between lines. Over the entire image, the slow-scan coordinate monotonically increases from $0$ to $L$, and the elapsed time advances from $t=0$ at the first line to $t=T$ at the last line. For a uniform raster with line index mapping linearly to time, the time $t$ at which a given slow-scan position $y$ is acquired is approximately proportional to $y$:
$$
t(y) \;\approx\; \frac{T}{L}\, y,
$$
neglecting higher-order effects such as flyback dead times and assuming sufficiently many lines that the discrete nature of lines can be approximated as continuous.

Substituting this relationship into the drift mapping yields, for a constant drift directed along the fast-scan axis $x$ (so $\mathbf{v}_{\text{d}} = (v_{\text{d}}, 0)$),
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
x_{\text{true}} \\
y_{\text{true}}
\end{pmatrix}
\;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
x_{\text{scan}} \\
y_{\text{scan}}
\end{pmatrix}
\;+\;
\begin{pmatrix}
v_{\text{d}}\, t(y_{\text{scan}}) \\
0
\end{pmatrix}
\;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
x_{\text{scan}} \\
y_{\text{scan}}
\end{pmatrix}
\;+\;
\begin{pmatrix}
v_{\text{d}}\, \dfrac{T}{L}\, y_{\text{scan}} \\
0
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
This relation is an affine transformation that can be written as a linear deformation (to first order, ignoring any overall translation) with deformation gradient $\mathbf{F}$ acting on the scanner coordinate:
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
x_{\text{true}} \\
y_{\text{true}}
\end{pmatrix}
\;=\;
\underbrace{\begin{pmatrix}
1  \gamma \\
0  1
\end{pmatrix}}_{\mathbf{F}}
\begin{pmatrix}
x_{\text{scan}} \\
y_{\text{scan}}
\end{pmatrix},
\qquad
\gamma \;=\; \frac{v_{\text{d}}\, T}{L}.
$$
Qualitatively, because each successive line is acquired at a later time, the constant drift along $x$ displaces each line by a slightly different $x$-offset that increases linearly with $y$. Consequently, a vertical lattice vector (parallel to $y$) appears tilted in the recorded image, and square features appear as parallelograms; this is the hallmark of a shear distortion.

The apparent shear strain is defined here as the off-diagonal component $\gamma$ of the deformation gradient, which quantifies the accumulated displacement in the fast-scan direction per unit extent in the slow-scan direction. Using the given values,
convert $v_{\text{d}}$ to nanometers per minute:
$$
v_{\text{d}} \;=\; 0.5\ \text{\AA}/\text{min} \;=\; 0.05\ \text{nm}/\text{min}.
$$
Compute the total drift displacement along $x$ over the image duration:
$$
\Delta x \;=\; v_{\text{d}}\, T \;=\; \left(0.05\ \frac{\text{nm}}{\text{min}}\right)\,(10\ \text{min}) \;=\; 0.5\ \text{nm}.
$$
Divide by the slow-scan extent $L$ to obtain the shear strain:
$$
\gamma \;=\; \frac{\Delta x}{L} \;=\; \frac{0.5\ \text{nm}}{10\ \text{nm}} \;=\; 0.05.
$$
As a pure number, rounded to four significant figures, this is
$$
\gamma \;=\; 0.05000.
$$
